```javascript
function postToWordpress(postContent) {
  var selectionText = postContent || '';
  var document = window.document;
  var location = document.location;

  var wordpressUrl = 'https://wordpress.com/post/paidpursuit.wordpress.com';
  var url = wordpressUrl + "?url=" + encodeURIComponent(location.href) +
                         "&title=" + encodeURIComponent(document.title) +
                         "&text=" + encodeURIComponent(selectionText) +
                         "&v=5";

  var popup = function() {
    window.open(url, "t", "toolbar=0,resizable=1,scrollbars=1,status=1,width=660,height=570") || (location.href = url);
  };

  // Firefox requires a slight delay
  if (/Firefox/.test(navigator.userAgent)) {
    setTimeout(popup, 0);
  } else {
    popup();
  }
}

// To use the function with a selected string as post content.
postToWordpress('Your selected string here.');
```

Make sure to call the `postToWordpress` function with the actual content you want to post as the argument. The function assumes you want to create a post on WordPress using the current page's URL and title, with the additional content you provide. If you are looking to make this function dynamic, such as taking the post's URL and title as parameters, you would have to modify the function accordingly.

