As of my last knowledge update in early 2023, directly saving a draft through a URL parameter is not possible without using the WordPress REST API or another backend method that involves authentication to interact with your WordPress site programmatically.

For automated draft saving, you would need to explore the WordPress REST API and write a function that makes authenticated POST requests to create a draft. This process typically involves Oauth or cookie authentication and is considerably more complex than opening a URL in a new window.

Creating a WordPress draft post using the WordPress.com REST API requires authentication and client-side requests cannot be made due to the CORS policy. However, for illustration purposes, here is how a function to make an API request to create a new draft post might look like. Remember, in practice, this request needs to be made from a server-side application or a platform that is CORS-compliant with proper authentication.

You'll need a WordPress.com OAuth token to use the API for authentication. Below is a conceptual example that you shouldn't use as-is for security and functionality purposes.

```javascript
function saveDraftToWordpress(postContent, oauthToken) {
  // Replace with your actual site ID or domain
  var siteId = 'your-site-id-or-domain.com';
  var apiEndpoint = `https://public-api.wordpress.com/rest/v1.1/sites/${siteId}/posts/new`;

  // Setup the API request payload
  var postData = {
    title: "Draft Title", // Put your desired post title here
    content: postContent,
    status: 'draft' // This ensures the post is saved as a draft
  };

  // Prepare the XMLHttpRequest
  var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
  xhr.open('POST', apiEndpoint, true);
  xhr.setRequestHeader('Authorization', 'Bearer ' + oauthToken);
  xhr.setRequestHeader('Content-Type', 'application/json');
  xhr.onreadystatechange = function() {
    if (xhr.readyState === 4) { // Done
      if (xhr.status === 201) { // Created
        console.log('Draft saved:', JSON.parse(xhr.responseText));
      } else {
        console.error('Error saving draft:', xhr.responseText);
      }
    }
  };

  // Send the API request
  xhr.send(JSON.stringify(postData));
}

// To use the function, you must pass in the desired post content and a valid OAuth token.
saveDraftToWordpress('Your post content here', 'YourOAuthToken');
```

When using the WordPress API:

1. You need to replace `your-site-id-or-domain.com` with the actual domain name or site ID of your WordPress blog.
2. Use the actual title for the draft post you want to save.
3. Replace `'YourOAuthToken'` with your actual OAuth token. Obtaining this token involves registering an application with WordPress.com, directing the user to a login screen, and receiving the token after they have authenticated.

Due to the sensitive nature of OAuth tokens which grant access to your WordPress account, you should handle them securely and never expose them in client-side code (like JavaScript running in the browser). Typically, operations like this should be executed server-side, making sure all credentials are kept secure.

Remember that you will need to abide by WordPress.com's API documentation and guidelines, and also handle authorization properly for your use case.

