You've created a new folder in your Firebase storage and uploaded an image there, which is a good start. And when you set the `image` field of your `PastMK` document to a string like `"PastMK/some.png"`, you're telling your app to look in the `PastMK` folder in Firebase storage for the `some.png` image.

However, you also need to make sure that the security rules for your Firebase storage allow anyone to read from the `PastMK` folder. You can do this by adding a new rule to your storage security rules, like this:

```
service firebase.storage {
  match /b/{bucket}/o {
    // ...

    // Allow anyone to read from the PastMK folder
    match /PastMK/{allPaths=**} {
      allow read;
    }
  }
}
```

This rule allows anyone to read any file in the `PastMK` folder. Make sure to update the bucket name (`{bucket}`) to the name of your Firebase storage bucket.

Once you've updated your storage rules, make sure to publish the changes to ensure that they take effect. Then try reloading your app to see if the image displays correctly.

The error message suggests that you are trying to use a Firebase module that has not been properly installed in your Android project. To resolve this issue, follow these steps:

1. In your `MainApplication.java` file, add the following import statement at the top:

   ```java
   import io.invertase.firebase.app.ReactNativeFirebaseAppPackage;
   ```

2. Inside the `getPackages` method of the `MainApplication` class, add the following line:

   ```java
     new ReactNativeFirebaseAppPackage()
   ```

   For example, the `getPackages` method should look like this:

   ```java
   @Override
   protected List<ReactPackage> getPackages() {
       return Arrays.asList(
               new MainReactPackage(),
               // ... other packages
               new ReactNativeFirebaseAppPackage() // Add this line
       );
   }
   ```

3. Save your changes to `MainApplication.java` and try rebuilding your Android project.

If you still see the error message after following these steps, make sure that you have properly installed all of the necessary Firebase modules for your project and that your `google-services.json` file is properly configured. You can also try stopping Metro and restarting it in your current project directory to see if that resolves the issue with `AppRegistry.registerComponent`.

