To ensure that text is visible on a random background color, you can implement a contrast check between the text color and the background color. One approach to do this is by using the WCAG (Web Content Accessibility Guidelines) Luminance formula for determining contrast ratio. Below is a sample algorithm in C# to achieve this visibility:

1. First, let's create a helper function to compute the luminance of a color. This function takes an sRGB color value and converts it to a linear value:

```csharp
private static double CalculateLuminance(Color color)
{
    double GetLinear(double channelValue)
    {
        return (channelValue <= 0.03928) ? channelValue / 12.92 : Math.Pow((channelValue + 0.055) / 1.055, 2.4);
    }

    // Normalize the color channels to 0-1 range.
    double r = color.R / 255d;
    double g = color.G / 255d;
    double b = color.B / 255d;

    // Linearize sRGB color channels.
    double rLinear = GetLinear(r);
    double gLinear = GetLinear(g);
    double bLinear = GetLinear(b);

    // Calculate relative luminance.
    double luminance = 0.2126 * rLinear + 0.7152 * gLinear + 0.0722 * bLinear;
    return luminance;
}
```

2. Next, create a function to compute the contrast ratio between two colors using their luminance values:

```csharp
private static double CalculateContrastRatio(Color color1, Color color2)
{
    double luminance1 = CalculateLuminance(color1);
    double luminance2 = CalculateLuminance(color2);

    // Ensure luminance1 is the larger value.
    if (luminance2 > luminance1)
    {
        double temp = luminance1;
        luminance1 = luminance2;
        luminance2 = temp;
    }

    double contrastRatio = (luminance1 + 0.05) / (luminance2 + 0.05);

    return contrastRatio;
}
```

3. Now, you can use these functions to ensure visible text by checking the contrast ratio and adjusting the text color if necessary:

```csharp
private static Color EnsureTextVisibility(Color textColor, Color backgroundColor, double minContrastRatio = 4.5)
{
    double contrastRatio = CalculateContrastRatio(textColor, backgroundColor);

    if (contrastRatio >= minContrastRatio)
    {
        return textColor;
    }

    double luminanceBackground = CalculateLuminance(backgroundColor);

    // If background color is too dark, set the text color to white, otherwise set it to black.
    return luminanceBackground < 0.5 ? Color.White : Color.Black;
}
```

4. Finally, when generating an image with text, check and adjust the text color if needed:

```csharp
Color randomBackgroundColor = ... // Generate a random background color.
Color randomTextColor = ... // Generate a random text color.

Color visibleTextColor = EnsureTextVisibility(randomTextColor, randomBackgroundColor);
```

